<dl id="n12069c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12069c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12069c"> 69(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> like a Montgomery / horse shod backwards</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Les Montgommery &eacute;taient, peut-&ecirc;tre, les plus grands personnages du pays; ils brillaient au premier rang parmi les huguenots dans ce coin de province dont fait partie le Mont Saint-Michel, l&apos;Avranchin. Jacques, sieur de Lorges, comte de Montgommery, originaire d&apos;Ecosse, attach&eacute; au service de Fran&ccedil;ois 1er, avait eu un fils Gabriel Ier, dit le Grand Montgommery, celui-l&agrave; m&ecirc;me qui avait bless&eacute; &agrave; mort, dans une joute d&apos;armes, le roi Henri II. Mari&eacute; avec Isabeau de la Tiral qui fut, apr&egrave;s sa mort, dame de Ducey, il eut quatre gar&ccedil;ons et quatre filles. Il fut d&eacute;capit&eacute; en 1574, mais la sentence de villenage port&eacute;e sur ses enfants n&apos;eut pas de suites. Son fils a&icirc;n&eacute;, Gabriel II, mari&eacute; &agrave; Suzanne de Boucquetot dont il eut cinq fils et une fille, fut pour le Mont un terrible adversaire. On sait qu&apos;il faillit s&apos;emparer par ruse de l&apos;abbaye-forteresse, dans la nuit du 29 au 30 septembre 1591. / Cette tragique aventure le rendit c&eacute;l&egrave;bre et odieux dans le pays; tout homme vindicatif, injuste, impie et cruel, &eacute;tait imm&eacute;diatement ap- <font color="green">[252]</font> parent&eacute; par le peuple &agrave; Montgommery, tant et si bien qu&apos;on ne distingua plus entre eux les membres de la famille. On ne faisait aucune diff&eacute;rence entre Jacques ni les deux Gabriel. La fatalit&eacute;, qui avait pes&eacute; sur les Montgommery, dont le second chef &eacute;tait devenu dans la langue populaire &laquo;celui qui avait tu&eacute; le roi&raquo; (et un autre a&iuml;eul en jouant, n&apos;avait-il pas br&ucirc;l&eacute; cruellement, avec un tison, le roi Fran&ccedil;ois 1er?), avait encore accru leur renomm&eacute;e. La l&eacute;gende le repr&eacute;sentait comme errant sans cesse sur la c&ocirc;te normande, de Coutances &agrave; Pontorson. Pas un seul ch&acirc;teau qu&apos;il ne visit&acirc;t tous les mois. Il venait battre de la fausse monnaie &agrave; Tombelaine; la nuit, d&eacute;trousseur de grands chemins, ferrant son cheval au rebours, afin de d&eacute;pister ceux qui osaient se lancer &agrave; sa poursuite, il arr&ecirc;tait les p&egrave;lerins attard&eacute;s; devenu le diable en personne, d&egrave;s qu&apos;il &eacute;tait en selle, il martyrisait les pauvres pr&ecirc;tres qu&apos;il for&ccedil;ait de c&eacute;l&eacute;brer des messes sacril&egrave;ges dans ses pr&ecirc;ches de Chasseguay, de Cormeray et de Ducey. <br><font color="green">[The Montgommerys were, perhaps, the greatest of the land; they were among the first of the Huguenots in this corner of the province of which Mont Saint-Michel was a part, the Avrancin. Jacques, sire of Lorges, count of Montgommery, originally Scottish, in the service of Fran&ccedil;ois I, had a son Gabriel I, called the Great Montgommery, the same one who had mortally wounded, in a joust, Henry II. Married to Isabeau de la Tiral who was, after his death, dame of Ducey, he had four boys and four girls. He was beheaded in 1574, but the sentence of villenage against his children was never executed. His elder son, Gabriel II, married to Suzanne de Boucquetot with whom he had five sons and a daughter, was a terrible enemy of the Mont. We know that he failed to take the abbey-fortress by guile on the night of 29 and 30 August 1591. / This tragic adventure made him famous and infamous in the land. Any person who was vindictive, unjust, impious or cruel, was immediately likened by the people to Montgommery, so much that one ceased to distinguish between the members of the family. No difference was made between Jacques and the two Gabriels. The fatality that had struck the Montgommerys, whose second in command had become in popular parlance &ldquo;the one who killed the king&rdquo; (and had not another ancestor, while playing, cruelly burned King Fran&ccedil;ois I with a cinder?), had only made them more infamous. The legend represented him as ceaselessy roaming the Normandy coast, from Coutances to Pontorson. Not a single castle that he did not visit every month; he tried to spend counterfeit money in Tombelaine; at night <mark>he traveled with a horse shod backwards</mark> to confuse those who attempted to follow him, he arrested pilgrims who were late; having become the devil himself, as soon as he was on horseback, he martyred poor priests whom he forced to say sacrilegious masses in his parishes of Chasseguay, Cormeray and de Ducey.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 252-3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
